        <h2 id="what-are-instagram-reels">What Are Instagram Reels?</h2>
        <p>Instagram Reels are short-form, vertical videos (9:16 aspect ratio) lasting up to 90 seconds that Instagram distributes to both followers and non-followers through its recommendation algorithm.</p>
        <p>Meta launched Reels in August 2020 as a direct response to <a href="/glossary/tiktok-seo/">TikTok</a>'s explosive growth. The format quickly became Instagram's fastest-growing feature, and by 2024, Reels accounted for over 50% of time spent on the platform according to Meta's earnings calls. Unlike traditional Instagram posts that primarily reach your existing followers, Reels get pushed to new audiences through the Reels tab and Explore page.</p>
        <p>That distribution model is the key differentiator. A business account with 500 followers can get 50,000 views on a single Reel if the content resonates. Instagram's head Adam Mosseri has repeatedly stated that Reels are the best way to grow reach on the platform.</p>
        <h2 id="why-do-instagram-reels-matter">Why Do Instagram Reels Matter?</h2>
        <p>Reels are Instagram's primary growth and discovery mechanism. If you're not creating Reels, you're leaving the biggest reach opportunity on the platform untouched.</p>
        <ul>
        <li><strong>Highest organic reach of any Instagram format</strong>. Reels reach 2-3x more non-followers than static posts or carousels, according to Hootsuite's 2024 Social Trends report</li>
        <li><strong>Algorithm priority</strong>. Instagram actively boosts Reels in the main feed, Explore page, and dedicated Reels tab. Meta has been transparent about prioritizing video.</li>
        <li><strong>Cross-platform distribution</strong>. Reels can be shared to Facebook Reels automatically, doubling your distribution with zero extra work</li>
        <li><strong>Purchase influence</strong> ,  44% of Instagram users shop weekly on the platform, and Reels with product tags drive direct <a href="/glossary/social-commerce/">social commerce</a> conversions</li>
        <li><strong>SMB equalizer</strong>. The algorithm cares about content quality, not account size. Small businesses compete on the same playing field as major brands.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>For local businesses and SMBs, Reels represent the cheapest way to reach thousands of potential customers without spending a dollar on ads.</p>
        <h2 id="how-instagram-reels-work">How Instagram Reels Work</h2>
        <h3 id="creation">Creation</h3>
        <p>You record or upload <a href="/glossary/vertical-video/">vertical video</a> through the Instagram app (or schedule via Meta Business Suite). Reels support music from Instagram's library, voiceover, text overlays, AR effects, and basic editing features like trim, speed adjustment, and align (for seamless transitions).</p>
        <h3 id="distribution-algorithm">Distribution Algorithm</h3>
        <p>Instagram's Reels algorithm evaluates content based on four primary signals:</p>
        <ol>
        <li><strong>User activity</strong>. What Reels has this user liked, shared, saved, and watched fully before?</li>
        <li><strong>Interaction history</strong>. Has this user engaged with your account previously?</li>
        <li><strong>Reel information</strong>. Audio track, video content (Instagram's AI analyzes the actual frames), caption text, and hashtags</li>
        <li><strong>Creator information</strong>. Your overall <a href="/glossary/engagement-rate/">engagement rate</a>, posting frequency, and content history</li>
        </ol>
        <p>The algorithm serves your Reel to a small test audience first. If they watch it fully, share it, or save it, Instagram expands distribution. Poor initial performance means limited reach. Watch time is the single most important metric.</p>
        <h3 id="monetization">Monetization</h3>
        <p>Creators can earn through Instagram's bonus programs (invitation-only), brand partnerships, and product tagging via <a href="/glossary/instagram-shopping/">Instagram Shopping</a>. For businesses, the real monetization isn't direct payouts. It's the leads and sales generated by reaching new audiences.</p>
        <h2 id="types-of-instagram-reels">Types of Instagram Reels</h2>
        <p>Different Reel formats serve different marketing goals:</p>
        <ul>
        <li><strong>Educational Reels</strong>. Quick tips, how-tos, or myth-busting. These perform well for service businesses. A dentist explaining "3 signs you need a root canal" or a realtor walking through "What to expect at closing."</li>
        <li><strong>Behind-the-scenes Reels</strong>. Showing your process, workspace, or team. Builds trust and humanizes the business. <a href="/glossary/behind-the-scenes-content/">Behind-the-scenes content</a> consistently gets high saves.</li>
        <li><strong>Trending audio Reels</strong>. Using <a href="/glossary/trending-sound/">trending sounds</a> or music to ride algorithmic waves. These get boosted by Instagram when a sound is peaking. Timing matters. Jump on trends within 48 hours.</li>
        <li><strong>Testimonial and result Reels</strong>. Before/after transformations, customer stories, or project showcases. High <a href="/glossary/social-proof/">social proof</a> value. These convert followers into customers.</li>
        <li><strong>Collab Reels</strong>. Co-created with another account, appearing on both profiles simultaneously. Doubles reach instantly.</li>
        </ul>
        <h2 id="instagram-reels-examples">Instagram Reels Examples</h2>
        <p><strong>Example 1: A plumber growing a local following</strong>
        A plumbing company in Denver posts 3 Reels per week showing satisfying drain unclogging videos and quick plumbing tips. One 15-second drain video hits 800,000 views. They gain 4,000 followers in a month. Most of them local. Combined with SEO content from theStacc driving local search traffic, they build both social and organic channels simultaneously.</p>
        <p><strong>Example 2: A bakery driving foot traffic</strong>
        A neighborhood bakery films 10-second Reels of cake decorating and bread baking. No fancy editing. Just close-up shots with trending audio. Average: 15,000 views per Reel on a 2,000-follower account. They tag their location on every post, and foot traffic increases 20% on days they post.</p>
        <p><strong>Example 3: A real estate agent who ignored Reels</strong>
        A realtor posted only static listing photos for 2 years and saw declining reach. After switching to Reels. Market updates, neighborhood tours, home-buying tips. Their monthly reach jumped from 3,000 to 45,000. Same follower count. Different format. Completely different results.</p>
        <h2 id="instagram-reels-vs-tiktok">Instagram Reels vs. TikTok</h2>
        <p>These formats compete directly, and businesses often wonder which one to prioritize.</p>
