        <p>Most businesses should post on both. The content creation effort is the same. You're making vertical videos either way.</p>
        <h2 id="instagram-reels-best-practices">Instagram Reels Best Practices</h2>
        <ul>
        <li><strong>Hook viewers in the first 1-2 seconds</strong>. If someone scrolls past your opening, watch time tanks and the algorithm buries the Reel. Start with movement, a question, or a surprising statement. Never start with a logo intro.</li>
        <li><strong>Optimize for saves and shares, not just likes</strong>. The algorithm weights saves and shares higher than likes. Create content people want to reference later (tips, checklists, tutorials) or share with friends.</li>
        <li><strong>Post 3-5 Reels per week</strong>. Consistency trains the algorithm. One viral Reel per month matters less than steady output. Accounts posting 4+ Reels weekly see 2x the reach of those posting once a week.</li>
        <li><strong>Use 3-5 relevant hashtags</strong>. Don't stuff 30 hashtags. Instagram's recommendation system relies more on content analysis than <a href="/glossary/hashtag/">hashtags</a> now, but a few targeted ones still help categorization. Use a <a href="/glossary/hashtag-strategy/">hashtag strategy</a> focused on your niche.</li>
        <li><strong>Pair Reels with SEO content</strong>. Social media drives brand awareness; SEO captures high-intent search traffic. theStacc publishes 30 SEO articles/month while you focus on creating Reels that build your audience.</li>
        </ul>
        <h2 id="frequently-asked-questions">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <h3 id="whats-the-ideal-length-for-instagram-reels">What's the ideal length for Instagram Reels?</h3>
        <p>Reels between 7-15 seconds tend to get the highest completion rates, which drives algorithmic distribution. However, educational content can perform well at 30-60 seconds if retention stays high.</p>
        <h3 id="do-instagram-reels-help-with-seo">Do Instagram Reels help with SEO?</h3>
        <p>Not directly. Reels don't rank in Google Search. But they drive brand awareness, website clicks, and social signals that indirectly support your <a href="/glossary/organic-traffic/">organic traffic</a> and brand search volume.</p>
        <h3 id="can-i-repost-tiktoks-as-reels">Can I repost TikToks as Reels?</h3>
        <p>Technically yes, but remove the TikTok watermark first. Instagram has confirmed that watermarked content from other platforms gets deprioritized by the algorithm.</p>
        <h3 id="should-businesses-use-trending-audio">Should businesses use trending audio?</h3>
        <p>Yes, when it fits your brand. Reels with <a href="/glossary/trending-audio/">trending audio</a> get an algorithmic boost during the trend's peak. But forced trend participation looks awkward. Skip trends that don't connect to your message.</p>
